    <exercise number="27">
        <statement>
            <p>The formula <m>F = \dfrac{9}{5}C + 32</m> converts the temperature in degrees Celsius to degrees Fahrenheit.
            <ol label="a">
                <li><p>What is the Fahrenheit temperature when it is <m>10\degree</m> Celsius?</p></li>
                <li><p>What is the Celsius temperature when it is <m>-4\degree</m> Fahrenheit?</p></li>
                <li><p>Choose appropriate <c>WINDOW</c> settings and graph the equation <m>y = \dfrac{9}{5}x + 32</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Find the slope and explain its meaning for this problem.</p></li>
                <li><p>Find the intercepts and explain their meanings for this problem.</p></li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer><p>
            <ol label="a">
                <li><p><m>50\degree</m>F</p></li>
                <li><p><m>-20\degree</m>C</p></li>
                <li><sidebyside width="40%"><image source="images/fig-ans-1-5-27.jpg"><description>GC graph</description></image></sidebyside></li>
                <li><p>The slope, <m>\frac{9}{5} = 1.8</m>, tells us that Fahrenheit temperatures increase by <m>1.8\degree</m> for each increase of <m>1\degree</m> Celsius.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>C</m>-intercept <m>\left(-17\frac{7}{9}, 0\right)</m>: <m>-17\frac{7}{9}\degree</m> C is the same as <m>0\degree</m>F; <m>F</m>-intercept <m>(0, 32)</m>: <m>0\degree</m>C is the same as <m>32\degree</m>F.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p></answer>
    </exercise>

